\paragraph{C.58: investment adjustment.}
BGS inherits the SW/CEE investment-adjustment-cost FOC. Around the steady state,
where \(S(1)=S'(1)=0\), only the second derivative \(S''\) affects the linear
row. The investment FOC can be read as
\begin{equation}
0=q^k_t
-\gamma^2S''(i_t-i_{t-1})
+\beta\gamma^2S''E_t(i_{t+1}-i_t),
\label{eq:bgs-c58-foc-ladder}
\end{equation}
after normalizing the investment-specific shock convention into the capital law.
Collecting \(i_t\) terms gives
\begin{equation}
i_t
=
\frac{1}{1+\beta}i_{t-1}
+\frac{\beta}{1+\beta}E_ti_{t+1}
+\frac{1}{(1+\beta)\gamma^2S''}q^k_t .
\label{eq:bgs-c58-derived-ladder}
\end{equation}
This row is the source of hump-shaped investment dynamics. A static \(i_t=q_t\)
relation would not be the BGS/SW capital-producer block.

\paragraph{C.55--C.56: direct household asset demand.}
The source level FOCs are
\begin{align}
E_tR^k_{t+1}
&=R^d_t\{1+\kappa(K_{h,t}-\bar K_h)\},\\
E_tR^b_{t+1}
&=R^d_t\{1+\kappa(B_{h,t}-\bar B_h)\}.
\label{eq:bgs-c55-c56-level-repeat}
\end{align}
The steady state has \(K_h=\bar K_h\) and \(B_h=\bar B_h\), so marginal
portfolio costs vanish at the expansion point. For capital claims, the
first-order movement is
\begin{equation}
R^kE_tr^k_{t+1}
=R\,r^d_t+R\kappa K_hk_{h,t}.
\label{eq:bgs-c55-first-order}
\end{equation}
Divide by \(R\) and rearrange:
\begin{equation}
\kappa K_hk_{h,t}
=\frac{R^k}{R}(E_tr^k_{t+1}-r^d_t).
\label{eq:bgs-c55-derived-ladder}
\end{equation}
The bond row is identical:
\begin{equation}
\kappa B_hb_{h,t}
=\frac{R^b}{R}(E_tr^b_{t+1}-r^d_t).
\label{eq:bgs-c56-derived-ladder}
\end{equation}
These rows are the household side of the QE mechanism. They tell us how much
private households absorb when bank or central-bank asset positions change. If
these rows are omitted, the model loses the direct-arbitrage margin that BGS
inherits from GK-style QE analysis.

\paragraph{C.57: efficient wage.}
The labor FOC in levels is
\begin{equation}
W^h_t=X_tL_t^{\sigma_l},
\qquad X_t=C_t-hC_{t-1}.
\label{eq:bgs-c57-level-repeat}
\end{equation}
Taking logs and using \eqref{eq:bgs-c52-habit-stock-linear} gives
\begin{equation}
w^h_t
=
\frac{1}{1-h/\gamma}c_t
-\frac{h/\gamma}{1-h/\gamma}c_{t-1}
+\sigma_ll_t .
\label{eq:bgs-c57-derived-ladder}
\end{equation}
This is the object that appears in the wage Phillips curve. It is not a wage
markup shock. The wage markup is \(w_t-w^h_t\), so a Phillips curve written
with \(w^h_t-w_t\) has the opposite sign by construction.

