\paragraph{C.60--C.65: production, marginal cost, utilization, and returns.}
The level production function uses effective capital services,
\begin{equation}
K^s_t=U_tK^p_{t-1},
\qquad
Y_{m,t}=e^{z_t}(K^s_t)^\alpha(\gamma^tL_t)^{1-\alpha}
-\gamma^t\Phi .
\label{eq:bgs-c60-c65-level-production-ladder}
\end{equation}
Cost minimization gives the real marginal-cost and factor-price relations
\begin{align}
W_t&=MC_t(1-\alpha)\frac{Y_{m,t}}{L_t},\\
\Psi'(U_t)K^p_{t-1}
&=MC_t\alpha\frac{Y_{m,t}}{U_t}.
\label{eq:bgs-c60-c65-factor-focs}
\end{align}
The labor-demand row implies
\begin{equation}
mct=w_t-z_t+\alpha(l_t-k^s_t),
\label{eq:bgs-c60-derived-ladder}
\end{equation}
and the marginal product row can be written as
\begin{equation}
mpk_t=w_t-k^s_t+l_t .
\label{eq:bgs-c61-derived-ladder}
\end{equation}
The capital return is the payoff identity
\begin{equation}
R^k_tQ_{t-1}=MC_tMPK_t+(1-\delta)Q_t,
\label{eq:bgs-c62-level-repeat-ladder}
\end{equation}
which linearizes to
\begin{equation}
R^kr^k_t
=MC^*MPK(mct+y_t-k^s_t)+(1-\delta)q_t-R^kq_{t-1}.
\label{eq:bgs-c62-derived-ladder}
\end{equation}
The utilization and production rows are
\begin{align}
k^s_t&=u_t+k^p_{t-1},\\
u_t&=\frac{1-\psi}{\psi}mpk_t,\\
y_t&=\Phi\{\alpha k^s_t+(1-\alpha)l_t+z_t\}.
\label{eq:bgs-c63-c65-derived-ladder}
\end{align}
The superscripts \(p\) and \(s\) are reader aids. The source often prints
\(k_t\) in both roles. A human can infer the role from context, but executable
code cannot. The return equation must use the effective-capital object in the
marginal product and the lagged purchase price in the payoff.

\paragraph{C.53--C.54: deposit rate and Fisher bridge.}
BGS separates the real funding return used by households and banks from the
nominal policy rate. In gross terms the source relation is
\begin{equation}
R^d_t=R^r_t\,v_{u,t},
\qquad
R^r_t=\frac{R^n_t}{E_t\Pi_{t+1}} .
\label{eq:bgs-c53-c54-level}
\end{equation}
In log-deviation notation this becomes
\begin{align}
r^d_t&=rr_t+v_{u,t},\\
rr_t&=r^n_t-E_t\pi_{t+1}.
\label{eq:bgs-c53-c54-derived}
\end{align}
The important point is that \(v_{u,t}\) is not a pure preference discount-factor
shock in this notation. It is a wedge between the policy real rate and the
deposit return that also enters the macro-financial bridge through capital
valuation and bank funding costs.

