\paragraph{C.59: capital accumulation and the investment shock.}
The level capital law is
\begin{equation}
K_t=(1-\delta)K_{t-1}
+v_{i,t}\left[1-S(I_t/I_{t-1})\right]I_t .
\label{eq:bgs-c59-level-repeat}
\end{equation}
At first order, the installed capital stock responds to lagged capital, current
investment, and the investment-specific efficiency term:
\begin{equation}
k^p_t
=
\frac{1-\delta}{\gamma}k^p_{t-1}
+\left(1-\frac{1-\delta}{\gamma}\right)i_t
+\left(1-\frac{1-\delta}{\gamma}\right)\chi_i v_{i,t}.
\label{eq:bgs-c59-general-shock-scale}
\end{equation}
The BGS printed row uses
\begin{equation}
\chi_i=(1+\beta)\gamma^2S''.
\label{eq:bgs-c59-source-shock-scale}
\end{equation}
That scale is the one preserved in the source-led BGS branch. A comparator code
may absorb part of \(\chi_i\) into the shock definition, but then it must say so
explicitly because the observable capital response to \(v_{i,t}\) changes.

