\begin{equation}
W^h_t=X_tL_t^{\sigma_l},
\qquad X_t=C_t-hC_{t-1}.
\label{eq:bgs-c57-level-repeat}
\end{equation}
Taking logs and using \eqref{eq:bgs-c52-habit-stock-linear} gives
\begin{equation}
w^h_t
=
\frac{1}{1-h/\gamma}c_t
-\frac{h/\gamma}{1-h/\gamma}c_{t-1}
+\sigma_ll_t .
\label{eq:bgs-c57-derived-ladder}
\end{equation}
This is the object that appears in the wage Phillips curve. It is not a wage
markup shock. The wage markup is \(w_t-w^h_t\), so a Phillips curve written
