\paragraph{C.69: capital-asset shadow FOC.}
The level condition is
\begin{equation}
\nu_{k,t}=\lambda_{k,t}\frac{\mu_t}{1+\mu_t}.
\label{eq:bgs-c69-level-repeat}
\end{equation}
Let lower-case hats denote proportional movements for positive steady-state
objects. Then
\begin{equation}
\widehat\nu_{k,t}
=\widehat\lambda_{k,t}
+\widehat\mu_t-\widehat{(1+\mu_t)}.
\label{eq:bgs-c69-first-pass-logdiff}
\end{equation}
Since
\[
\widehat{(1+\mu_t)}
=\frac{\mu}{1+\mu}\widehat\mu_t,
\]
we get
\begin{equation}
\widehat\nu_{k,t}-\widehat\lambda_{k,t}
=\frac{1}{1+\mu}\widehat\mu_t.
\label{eq:bgs-c69-logdiff}
\end{equation}
The steady-state FOC implies
\[
\frac{1}{1+\mu}=\frac{\lambda_k-\nu_k}{\lambda_k},
\]
so \eqref{eq:bgs-c69-logdiff} becomes
\begin{equation}
\frac{\lambda_k}{\lambda_k-\nu_k}
(\widehat\nu_{k,t}-\widehat\lambda_{k,t})
=\widehat\mu_t .
\label{eq:bgs-c69-derived-row}
\end{equation}
This row says that the incentive multiplier rises when the shadow value of
holding capital claims rises relative to the divertibility of those claims.
If $\lambda_{k,t}$ rises because depositors perceive capital assets as more
divertible, the same $\nu_{k,t}$ is not enough to support the old asset
position. The multiplier tightens.

\paragraph{C.70: bond shadow FOC.}
The bond FOC is
\begin{equation}
\nu_{b,t}=\lambda_b\frac{\mu_t}{1+\mu_t}.
\label{eq:bgs-c70-level-repeat}
\end{equation}
Because $\lambda_b$ is constant in the source row,
\[
\widehat\nu_{b,t}
=\frac{1}{1+\mu}\widehat\mu_t .
\]
Using \eqref{eq:bgs-c69-logdiff} gives
\begin{equation}
\widehat\nu_{b,t}
=\widehat\nu_{k,t}-\widehat\lambda_{k,t}.
\label{eq:bgs-c70-derived-row}
\end{equation}
C.70 is therefore not an independent bond-pricing equation. It is the
portfolio-composition implication of having one incentive multiplier and two
asset classes, one with time-varying divertibility and one with constant
divertibility.

