\begin{equation}
\nu_{k,t}
=\beta E_t\Omega_{t+1}(R^k_{t+1}-R^d_t).
\label{eq:bgs-c72-level-repeat}
\end{equation}
The first-order expansion has a discount-factor piece and an excess-return
piece:
\begin{align}
d\nu_{k,t}
&=\beta E_t\left[
d\Omega_{t+1}(R^k-R^d)
+\Omega\,d(R^k_{t+1}-R^d_t)
\right]
\nonumber\\
&=\beta\Omega E_t\left[
(R^k-R^d)\widehat\Omega_{t+1}
+R^kr^k_{t+1}-R^dr^d_t
\right].
\label{eq:bgs-c72-expanded}
\end{align}
With $d\nu_{k,t}=\nu_k\widehat\nu_{k,t}$ this is C.72. The bond shadow row is
identical:
\begin{equation}
\nu_b\widehat\nu_{b,t}
=\beta\Omega E_t\left[
(R^b-R^d)\widehat\Omega_{t+1}
+R^br^b_{t+1}-R^dr^d_t
\right].
\label{eq:bgs-c73-expanded}
\end{equation}
The two rows show why capital-return and bond-return ambiguities propagate
directly into the bank block. The capital-return convention determines
\(r^k_{t+1}\), which is the payoff on bank-held capital claims in the capital
shadow-value equation. The long-bond convention determines \(r^b_{t+1}\),
which is the payoff on bank-held government bonds in the bond shadow-value
equation. The bank discount-factor convention determines
\(\widehat\Omega_{t+1}\), which enters both asset-shadow equations.

\paragraph{C.74: shadow value of net worth.}
The level row for net worth is
\begin{equation}
\nu_{n,t}=\beta E_t\Omega_{t+1}R^d_t.
\label{eq:bgs-c74-level-repeat}
\end{equation}
Since the steady-state equation is $\nu_n=\beta\Omega R^d$, the normalized
first-order row is
\begin{equation}
\widehat\nu_{n,t}
=E_t\widehat\Omega_{t+1}+r^d_t.
\label{eq:bgs-c74-expanded}
\end{equation}
