discounted value of one extra internal unit earning the deposit return. This
is why C.74 is often a useful diagnostic row: if the model makes
$\widehat\nu_{n,t}$ respond to a risky return spread directly, something has
been moved from the asset-shadow rows into the net-worth row.

\paragraph{C.75: intermediary SDF sign and timing.}
The level object is
\begin{equation}
\Omega_t=\frac{\Lambda_t}{\Lambda_{t-1}}
\left[(1-\theta)+\theta(1+\mu_t)\nu_{n,t}\right].
\label{eq:bgs-c75-level-repeat}
\end{equation}
Define
\[
M_t=\frac{\Lambda_t}{\Lambda_{t-1}},
\qquad
H_t=(1-\theta)+\theta(1+\mu_t)\nu_{n,t}.
\]
Then
\begin{equation}
\Omega\widehat\Omega_t
=\Omega\widehat M_t
+\theta\left((1+\mu)\nu_n\widehat\nu_{n,t}
+\nu_n\mu\widehat\mu_t\right).
\label{eq:bgs-c75-product-rule-expanded}
\end{equation}
The second term is not ambiguous. It is simply the derivative of the
continuing-bank value bracket. The ambiguity is entirely in $\widehat M_t$.
The source states the deposit-pricing normalization
\begin{equation}
\frac{\Lambda_t}{\Lambda_{t-1}}R^d_{t-1}=1.
\label{eq:bgs-c75-deposit-normalization-expanded}
\end{equation}
