\paragraph{C.75: intermediary SDF sign and timing.}
The level object is
\begin{equation}
\Omega_t=\frac{\Lambda_t}{\Lambda_{t-1}}
\left[(1-\theta)+\theta(1+\mu_t)\nu_{n,t}\right].
\label{eq:bgs-c75-level-repeat}
\end{equation}
Define
\[
M_t=\frac{\Lambda_t}{\Lambda_{t-1}},
\qquad
H_t=(1-\theta)+\theta(1+\mu_t)\nu_{n,t}.
\]
Then
\begin{equation}
\Omega\widehat\Omega_t
=\Omega\widehat M_t
+\theta\left((1+\mu)\nu_n\widehat\nu_{n,t}
+\nu_n\mu\widehat\mu_t\right).
\label{eq:bgs-c75-product-rule-expanded}
\end{equation}
The second term is not ambiguous. It is simply the derivative of the
continuing-bank value bracket. The ambiguity is entirely in $\widehat M_t$.
The source states the deposit-pricing normalization
\begin{equation}
\frac{\Lambda_t}{\Lambda_{t-1}}R^d_{t-1}=1.
\label{eq:bgs-c75-deposit-normalization-expanded}
\end{equation}
Log-linearizing \eqref{eq:bgs-c75-deposit-normalization-expanded} gives
\begin{equation}
\widehat M_t=-r^d_{t-1}.
\label{eq:bgs-c75-negative-sdf-expanded}
\end{equation}
Substituting this into \eqref{eq:bgs-c75-product-rule-expanded} gives the
standard log-discounting branch:
\begin{equation}
\Omega\widehat\Omega_t
=-\Omega r^d_{t-1}
+\theta\left((1+\mu)\nu_n\widehat\nu_{n,t}
+\nu_n\mu\widehat\mu_t\right).
\label{eq:bgs-c75-negative-branch-expanded}
\end{equation}
The printed Appendix C row instead displays the first term with a positive
sign:
\begin{equation}
\Omega\widehat\Omega_t
=+\Omega r^d_{t-1}
+\theta\left((1+\mu)\nu_n\widehat\nu_{n,t}
+\nu_n\mu\widehat\mu_t\right).
\label{eq:bgs-c75-positive-branch-expanded}
\end{equation}
Both readings keep the same continuation-value derivative. They differ only
in the sign/timing translation of the household discount-factor component.
That difference is not cosmetic, because \(\widehat\Omega_{t+1}\) is the bank
valuation object used to price capital claims, government bonds, and internal
bank funds. A candidate using the positive printed reading and a candidate
using the negative deposit-Euler reading are different financial-transition
systems even if all other rows are identical.
The official RES online appendix is the source for the positive printed C.75
branch. The negative row is the local log-discounting check implied by applying
the stated normalization literally. The report therefore preserves both rows
as a branch pair unless a later source/code/economic audit justifies choosing
one for a specific candidate surface.

\paragraph{C.77: new-bank starting asset base.}
The source level row states
\begin{equation}
N_{n,t}
=\omega\left(Q_{t-1}K_{b,t-1}
+Q^b_{t-1}B_{b,t-1}\right).
\label{eq:bgs-c77-level-repeat}
\end{equation}
The linear source-favored row is therefore
\begin{equation}
N_n n_{n,t}
=\frac{\omega}{\gamma}
\left[
K_b(q_{t-1}+k_{b,t-1})
+Q^bB_b(q^b_{t-1}+b_{b,t-1})
\right].
\label{eq:bgs-c77-bank-held-expanded}
\end{equation}
The phrase ``bank-held'' is doing real work. The source row uses
$K_{b,t-1}$ and $B_{b,t-1}$, not total $K_{t-1}$ and $B_{t-1}$. A total-asset
comparator would instead be
The D264 official-source pass verified that this is the published RES online
appendix row, not merely a legacy extract or a local YAML convention.
\begin{equation}
N_n n^{T}_{n,t}
=\frac{\omega}{\gamma}
\left[
K_b(q_{t-1}+k_{t-1})
+Q^bB_b(q^b_{t-1}+b_{t-1})
\right].
\label{eq:bgs-c77-total-asset-expanded}
\end{equation}
Subtracting \eqref{eq:bgs-c77-bank-held-expanded} from
\eqref{eq:bgs-c77-total-asset-expanded} gives
\begin{equation}
N_n(n^T_{n,t}-n^B_{n,t})
=\frac{\omega}{\gamma}
\left[
K_b(k_{t-1}-k_{b,t-1})
+Q^bB_b(b_{t-1}-b_{b,t-1})
\right].
\label{eq:bgs-c77-branch-difference-expanded}
\end{equation}
The difference is zero only if total asset stocks move one-for-one with
