The level row for net worth is
\begin{equation}
\nu_{n,t}=\beta E_t\Omega_{t+1}R^d_t.
\label{eq:bgs-c74-level-repeat}
\end{equation}
Since the steady-state equation is $\nu_n=\beta\Omega R^d$, the normalized
first-order row is
\begin{equation}
\widehat\nu_{n,t}
=E_t\widehat\Omega_{t+1}+r^d_t.
\label{eq:bgs-c74-expanded}
\end{equation}
There is no excess-return spread here. The marginal value of net worth is the
discounted value of one extra internal unit earning the deposit return. This
is why C.74 is often a useful diagnostic row: if the model makes
$\widehat\nu_{n,t}$ respond to a risky return spread directly, something has
been moved from the asset-shadow rows into the net-worth row.

