The purchase identities come from the asset-market clearing rows
\begin{equation}
K_t=K_{b,t}+K_{h,t}+K_{cb,t},
\qquad
B_t=B_{b,t}+B_{h,t}+B_{cb,t}.
\label{eq:bgs-level-asset-clearing}
\end{equation}
Divide the capital identity by the steady-state aggregate capital stock and
take first-order log deviations:
\begin{equation}
k_t
=\frac{K_b}{K}k_{b,t}
+\frac{K_h}{K}k_{h,t}
+\frac{K_{cb}}{K}k_{cb,t}.
\end{equation}
BGS defines the central-bank purchase share $x_{k,t}$ as the residual asset
quantity held outside banks and households, so the same equation becomes
\begin{equation}
x_{k,t}=k_t-\frac{K_b}{K}k_{b,t}-\frac{K_h}{K}k_{h,t}.
\label{eq:bgs-capital-purchase-residual-derived}
\end{equation}
The bond identity gives
\begin{equation}
x_{b,t}=b_t-\frac{B_b}{B}b_{b,t}-\frac{B_h}{B}b_{h,t}.
\label{eq:bgs-bond-purchase-residual-derived}
\end{equation}
Finally, the observable rows
\begin{equation}
\widetilde K_{cb,t}=x_{k,t}QK/(4Y),
\qquad
\widetilde B_{cb,t}=x_{b,t}Q^bB/(4Y)
\label{eq:bgs-purchase-observable-derived}
\end{equation}
convert model purchase quantities into annualized GDP shares. The factor
$4Y$ is therefore a measurement denominator. It should not enter the bank
balance sheet, the household FOC, or the incentive constraint except through
the translation between observed QE series and model quantities.
The same measurement logic applies to liquidity:
\begin{equation}
\widetilde L_t=\frac{L^q_t}{P_tY_t}
\quad\hbox{is a process/observable, while}\quad
L^q_t
\quad\hbox{is the level object in C.71 and bank net worth.}
\label{eq:bgs-liquidity-measurement-vs-bank-level}
\end{equation}
Because steady-state liquidity is zero, $L^q_t$ is an absolute deviation in
the bank equations. The scaled process $\widetilde L_t$ can be used to match
data, but it cannot be logged and substituted mechanically into the bank FOC.

\paragraph{C.80: actual versus notional policy rate.}
The source writes the lower-bound row in log-deviation form as
\begin{equation}
r^n_t=\max\{0,r^s_t\}.
\label{eq:bgs-c80-derived-ladder}
\end{equation}
The notional rate \(r^s_t\) is the shadow Taylor-rule object. The actual rate
\(r^n_t\) is the policy rate that enters the Fisher relation and observed-rate
mapping. Therefore the lower-bound row is not merely a truncation of a data
series. It changes the equilibrium law of motion because the expected future
path of the notional rate determines the expected duration of the binding
spell.

