\paragraph{C.78: fiscal budget with tax feedback.}
The level government budget is
\begin{equation}
G_t+R^b_tQ^b_{t-1}B_{t-1}=Q^b_tB_t+T_t,
\label{eq:bgs-c78-level-budget-ladder}
\end{equation}
and taxes obey
\begin{equation}
T_t=T+\kappa_\tau(B_{t-1}-B).
\label{eq:bgs-c78-tax-rule-ladder}
\end{equation}
Substitute the tax rule into the budget constraint and expand around the
balanced-growth steady state. The inherited bond payoff contributes
\[
\frac{R^bQ^bB}{\gamma}(r^b_t+q^b_{t-1}+b_{t-1}),
\]
government spending contributes \(-Gg_t\), the tax feedback contributes
\(-\kappa_\tau b_{t-1}\), and the current market value of debt contributes
\[
Q^bB(q^b_t+b_t).
\]
Thus
\begin{equation}
\frac{R^bQ^bB}{\gamma}(r^b_t+q^b_{t-1}+b_{t-1})
-Gg_t-\kappa_\tau b_{t-1}
=Q^bB(q^b_t+b_t).
\label{eq:bgs-c78-derived-ladder}
\end{equation}
This row is not a monetary-policy reaction function. It is the accounting row
that keeps government debt, the long-bond price, taxes, and government
spending mutually consistent.

